SIMPLE: sewer
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sewer
<hw>Sew"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who
sews, or stitches.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small tortricid moth whose
larva sews together the edges of a leaf by means of silk; <as>as, the
apple-leaf <ex>sewer</ex> (<spn>Phoxopteris
nubeculana</spn>)</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sewer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sewer
<hw>Sew"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>sewiere</ets>, <ets>seuwiere</ets>, ultimately fr. L. <ets>ex</ets>
out + a derivative of <ets>aqua</ets> water; cf. OF. <ets>essevour</ets>
a drain, <ets>essever</ets>, <ets>esseuwer</ets>, <ets>essiaver</ets>,
to cause to flow, to drain, to flow, LL. <ets>exaquatorium</ets> a
channel through which water runs off. Cf. <er>Ewer</er>,
<er>Aquarium</er>.]</ety> <def>A drain or passage to carry off water and
filth under ground; a subterraneous channel, particularly in
cities.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sewer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sewer
<hw>Sew"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OE. <ets>assewer</ets>, and
<ets>asseour</ets>, OF. <ets>asseour</ets>, F. <ets>asseoir</ets> to
seat, to set, L. <ets>assidere</ets> to sit by; <ets>ad + sedere</ets>
to sit (cf. <er>Sit</er>); or cf. OE. <ets>sew</ets> pottage, sauce,
boiled meat, AS. <ets>se⟦aacute⟧w</ets> juice, Skr. <ets>su</ets> to
press out.]</ety> <def>Formerly, an upper servant, or household officer,
who set on and removed the dishes at a feast, and who also brought water
for the hands of the guests.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then the <qex>sewer</qex>⟦br⟧
Poured water from a great and golden ewer,⟦br⟧
That from their hands to a silver caldron ran.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sewerage</ent>⟦br⟧
